'''Alavida Health Inc.''' is a company headquartered in [[British Columbia]], Canada offering treatment of [[Alcohol abuse|alcohol use disorder]] that combines drug therapy and counselling. Alavida was founded by [[Chief executive officer|CEO]], Elliot Stone; Medical Director, Diane Rothon and Clinical Program Director, Terri-Lynn MacKay.
==History== Alavida Health Inc. was founded in 2016, located in British Columbia, Canada. It was founded by [[Chief executive officer]], Elliot Stone; Medical Director, Diane Rothon a former Chief [[Coroner]] of British Columbia with over 30 years experience in addiction medicine.<ref name=Leonhart>{{cite web | last=Leonhardt | first= David | title=Could Canadian Alcoholics Finally Get A Cure | publisher=[[Huffington Post]] | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/david-leonhardt/canadian-alcoholic-cure_b_10564174.html | accessdate=July 13, 2016 | date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>
==Treatment philosophy== The Alavida Method is based on a Finnish treatment model involving a combination of drug therapy and counselling that has been used in that country for more than 20 years. Alavida Health Ltd. has licensed this treatment program and adapted it to fit the Canadian market, currently focusing on British Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |last=Schaefer | first= Glen | title=Treatment making B.C. debut offers alcoholics the option of social drinking | publisher=The Province | url=http://www.theprovince.com/touch/story.html?id=11939999 | accessdate=July 13, 2016 | date=May 24, 2016}}</ref> The Alavida program can be used in conjunction with other therapy and programs such as [[SMART Recovery]], or as a preparatory program for abstinence.
Pharmacological extinction (commonly referred to as [[The Sinclair Method]]) is used to address the physiological elements of addiction. [[Naltrexone]], the medication used in the treatment, is taken before a person drinks alcohol. The FDA approved naltrexone as an alcohol abuse treatment in 1994.<ref name=Leonhart/>
