{{Infobox desalination plant | name = Ras Al-Khair Power and Desalination Plant | location_map = Saudi Arabia | location_map_width = | location_map_text = Location within Saudi Arabia | location = [[Ras Al-Khair]], [[Saudi Arabia]] | coordinates = {{coord|27|32|12.8|N|49|08|20.4|E|region:SA-04_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | estimated output = {{convert|1036|ML}} per day<ref name="Bennett1">{{cite news|last1=Bennett|first1=Anthony|title=Current challenges in energy recovery for desalination – Filtration + Separation|url=http://www.filtsep.com/view/40771/current-challenges-in-energy-recovery-for-desalination/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=www.filtsep.com|publisher=Elsevier Ltd|date=27 November 2014}}</ref> | cost = SR27 billion (US$7.2 billion)<ref name="WaterTechnology">{{cite web|title=Ras Al Khair Desalination Plant|url=http://www.water-technology.net/projects/-ras-al-khair-desalination-plant/|website=Water Technology|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> | technology = [[Multi-stage flash distillation|Multi-stage flashing]] and [[reverse osmosis]] | operation date = {{Start date|2014|04}}<ref name="StartsPumping">{{cite news|last1=Al-Suhaymi|first1=Obaid|title=World’s largest hybrid desalination plant starts pumping – ASHARQ AL-AWSAT English|url=http://english.aawsat.com/2014/04/article55331508/worlds-largest-hybrid-desalination-plant-starts-pumping|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=ASHARQ AL-AWSAT English|agency=Asharq Al-Awsat|date=23 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202001354/http://english.aawsat.com/2014/04/article55331508/worlds-largest-hybrid-desalination-plant-starts-pumping|archive-date=2017-02-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> | website = {{URL|http://www.swcc.gov.sa}} }}
The '''Ras Al-Khair Power and Desalination Plant''' is a [[power station|power]] and [[desalination plant]] located in [[Ras Al-Khair]] on the eastern coast of [[Saudi Arabia]]. It is operated by the [[Saline Water Conversion Corporation]] of Saudi Arabia. The plant began operating in April 2014 and, {{As of|2017|01|lc=y}}, is the world's largest hybrid water desalination plant.<ref name="StartsPumping" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Largest water desalination plant|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/425709-largest-water-desalination-plant|website=Guinness World Records|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> The project includes a power plant capable of producing 2400 [[Megawatt|MW]] of electricity.<ref name="StartsPumping" /> In 2015, it won the Global Water Awards "Desalination Plant of the Year" award.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Nominations Winners Global Water Awards|url=http://www.globalwaterawards.com/2015#DesalinationPlantOfTheYear|website=www.globalwaterawards.com|accessdate=20 January 2017|language=en|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000640/http://www.globalwaterawards.com/2015#DesalinationPlantOfTheYear|archivedate=2 February 2017|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Syed|first1=Imran|title=Saudi desalination tech wins global recognition|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/saudi-arabia/saudi-desalination-tech-wins-global-recognition/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=Saudi Gazette|date=26 October 2015}}</ref>
== History == Construction of the plant began in 2011.<ref name="WaterTechnology" /> Though originally slated to begin producing freshwater by the end of 2013,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Staff|first1=CW|title=Largest desalination plant in world 75% complete|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.com/article-22824-largest-desalination-plant-in-world-75-complete/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=www.constructionweekonline.com|date=9 June 2013}}</ref> the first freshwater produced from the plant was in early 2015.<ref name="Bennett2">{{cite news|last1=Bennett|first1=Anthony|title=Innovations and training in desalination – Filtration + Separation|url=http://www.filtsep.com/view/41714/innovations-and-training-in-desalination/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=www.filtsep.com|publisher=Elsevier Ltd}}</ref> Full commercial operation of the plant was achieved in March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ali|first1=Ajaz|title=Multi-commodity minerals hub to contribute $9b annually to non-oil GDP – Saudi Gazette|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/saudi-arabia/multi-commodity-minerals-hub-contribute-9b-annually-non-oil-gdp/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=Saudi Gazette|date=27 November 2016}}</ref>
The primary contractors for construction of the plant were the [[Doosan Group]] and [[Saudi Archirodon]].<ref name="WaterTechnology" /> Doosan was awarded the prime contract in September, 2010.<ref name="Bennett1" /> Additional contractors for the plant included [[Fluid Equipment Development Company]] for energy recovery devices, [[Siemens]] for generators, turbines, and related equipment, and [[Hyosung]] for various motors.<ref name="WaterTechnology" />
The plant has created 3,500 direct and indirect jobs.<ref name="StartsPumping" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Ras Al-Khair’s power plant to generate more jobs|url=http://www.arabnews.com/news/527721|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=Arab News|date=19 February 2014|language=en}}</ref>
== Operation == Water intake for the plant comes from the [[Persian Gulf]], on the shore of which the plant sits.<ref name="WaterTechnology" /> The plant includes five high-efficiency [[Combined-cycle gas turbine|gas turbines operated in combined cycle mode]] and in single mode.<ref name="WaterTechnology"/> It uses a hybrid system of eight [[Multi-stage flash distillation|multi-stage flashing]] units and 17 [[reverse osmosis]] units.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bennett|first1=Anthony|title=Advances in desalination energy recovery technologies – World Pumps|url=http://www.worldpumps.com/view/42505/advances-in-desalination-energy-recovery-technologies/|accessdate=20 January 2017|work=www.worldpumps.com|publisher=Elsevier Ltd}}</ref> Freshwater output from the plant is pumped via pipelines to [[Riyadh]] and [[Hafr Al-Batin]].<ref name="StartsPumping" /> Electricity and freshwater output from the plant also supply a nearby [[aluminium oxide]] refinery.<ref name="WaterTechnology" /> Of the 2400 MW electricity produced by the plant, 200 MW are used by the plant itself.<ref name="Bennett2" /> [[Effluent]] from the plant is processed locally by a dedicated wastewater treatment plant and discharged into the Persian Gulf.<ref name="WaterTechnology" />
